<font color="#FF0000">RUSHING</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb 15 23:19:14 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I'm feeling those feelings. This is one fine place<br>
to tune into to get boiling. All these platitudes we <br>
try to achieve.<br><br>
First up, we Vietnam Vets cannot let go. Lord knows<br>
we have tried. In the vernacular of those who would<br>
offer help or advice, &quot;If a Vet wants to find rest,<br>
just try to let go.&quot; Never happen, GI.<br><br>
I've stopped expecting some kind of forgiveness or<br>
inner peace. I think we mostly know that now. We are<br>
just like our brothers of I or II, or the crusades or Shiloh. It was just our time. It came and it stays.<br><br>
Those who would tell us there is insight in trying<br>
to understand why a Government made the decision it<br>
made, really weren't in the process. It was so simple.<br><br>
Basic training. Brutal, but pure. It was about having<br>
to do something and maybe getting to survive it. Turns<br>
out that was all we got to do. Am I the only one who<br>
gets tired of people telling me I have the solution to<br>
what haunts me? Contradiction in logic. We like to vent.<br><br>
We don't like any statement that even hints of insult<br>
to our buddies who died, who by the way could often be<br>
jerks or idiots. But they were right there with us trying<br>
to survive or be hero's or ignore it all or figure it out,<br>
or were so devastated by the scene they couldn't function.<br><br>
If anyone expects us to not be that way, well screw you.<br>
We cannot be any different. That can make us assholes,<br>
but it is a dedication to our fellow Vets, dead and alive,<br>
that we all feel a debt. It also is a reflection of what<br>
every one of us is deep within ourselves. AntiWar or <br>
blind patriot.<br><br>
I guess in a way we love the venting. Get me angry again<br>
anytime you want. Shit, sometimes if a couple of days go<br>
by and some damn experience hasn't crossed my mind, I feel<br>
empty. Maybe we ought to just get mellow with our dialog.<br><br>
If it gets angry, so be it. If it leads to some new insight,<br>
so be that. If we get bored, then we just leave the AO.<br><br>
What a mood I'm in tonight. Hearing impacts and thinking<br>
of the Essen Rock Festival in '69. Wouldn't mind talkin to<br>
a fellow Vet tonight or even an angry protestor. <br><br>
See Ya Back in the World,<br>

<p><code>-- carnival@ont.com  (JJ the Boonirat) </code><p>


